        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "## What `main.swift` does\n\nThe file imports SwiftUI and defines a single `ContentView` — a `View` whose `body` is a `Text(\"Hello\")`. Because it is named `main.swift`, Swift treats it as the entry point of an executable (implicit top-level/main), so this is effectively the entire demo app: a window/screen that renders the word \"Hello\".\n\nIt works, but it's dense (one-liner style) and lacks the standard SwiftUI scaffolding (`App`, `WindowGroup`, previews) that makes a project maintainable.\n\n## 3 concrete improvements\n\n### 1. Add a proper `@main` App entry point\nA bare `View` in `main.swift` works for a demo, but real apps need an `App` conforming type. Splitting this out makes the lifecycle explicit and portable (and lets you drop the special `main.swift` filename).\n\n```swift\nimport SwiftUI\n\n@main\nstruct DemoApp: App {\n    var body: some Scene {\n        WindowGroup {\n            ContentView()\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 2. Improve readability with standard formatting\nThe current one-liner (`struct ContentView: View { var body: some View { Text(\"Hello\") } }`) hides structure. Standard Swift formatting makes the view hierarchy scannable:\n\n```swift\nstruct ContentView: View {\n    var body: some View {\n        Text(\"Hello\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Add a `#Preview` for Xorge/iterable design\nA `#Preview` macro lets you see `ContentView` in Xcode's canvas without launching the simulator — critical for fast SwiftUI iteration:\n\n```swift\n#Preview {\n    ContentView()\n}\n```\n\nDrop all three into the file (with the `@main` App in a separate `DemoApp.swift` if you rename `main.swift`) and you get a conventional, previewable SwiftUI project. No files were modified.",
          "time": {
            "start": 1782860176706,
            "end": 1782860181860
          },
